After hinting that he might take the Falcons to Jacksonville, Fla., Mr. Smith lobbied for the development of the 72,000-seat Georgia Dome, which opened in 1992. The Dome was host to the 1994 Super Bowl and is scheduled to be the site of the 2000 game. Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





Mr. Smith lived in northwest Atlanta with his wife, Charlotte Lilliard Topping. The couple also maintained a plantation, called Seminole, in Thomasville. His philanthropic contributions include his support of the Fernbank Museum of Natural History, a youth foundation and the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra.Mr. Smith's son, Taylor, is the club president. Mr. Smith is also survived by four other children, Rankin M. Smith Jr., Carroll Smith Walraven, Dorothy Smith Knox and Karen Smith Owen, who all serve on the team's board of directors.Funeral arrangements are to be announced today, according to The Associated Press. Continue reading the main story






